@article{7cd86be51ef849829eeba555156f74f0,
  title     = "Women Grab Back: Exclusion, Policy Threat, and Women{\textquoteright}s Political Ambition",
  abstract  = "Previous work suggests that observing women officeholders increases women{\textquoteright}s political ambition. Yet, jumps in women{\textquoteright}s representation in the United States{\textquoteright} “Years of the Woman”—following the Anita Hill testimonies and the election of Donald Trump—are linked to women{\textquoteright}s exclusion from political decision-making. Drawing on focus groups with prospective women candidates, we theorize that exclusion when combined with a gendered policy threat increases women{\textquoteright}s political ambition. Using survey experiments replicated across different samples, we show that women who read about an all-male city council poised to legislate on women{\textquoteright}s rights report increased ambition compared with their pretreatment ambition levels and to women in other treatment groups. Women{\textquoteright}s increased sense of political efficacy drives these results. When women{\textquoteright}s rights are not under discussion, men{\textquoteright}s overrepresentation does not move (or even depresses) women{\textquoteright}s ambition. Seeing the policy consequences of their exclusion causes some women to seek a seat at the table.",
