  abstract  = "What does women{\textquoteright}s presence in political decision-making bodies signal to citizens? Do these signals differ based on the body{\textquoteright}s policy decisions? And do women and men respond to women{\textquoteright}s presence similarly? Though scholars have demonstrated the substantive and symbolic benefits of women{\textquoteright}s representation, little work has examined how women{\textquoteright}s presence affects citizens{\textquoteright} perceptions of democratic legitimacy.We test the relationship between representation and legitimacy beliefs through survey experiments on a nationally representative sample of U.S. citizens. First, we find that women{\textquoteright}s equal presence legitimizes decisions that go against women{\textquoteright}s interests. We show suggestive evidence that this effect is particularly pronounced among men, who tend to hold less certain views on women{\textquoteright}s rights. Second, across decision outcomes and issue areas, women{\textquoteright}s equal presence legitimizes decision-making processes and confers institutional trust and acquiescence. These findings add new theoretical insights into how, when, and for whom inclusive representation increases perceptions of democratic legitimacy.",
